The paper presents a sorting algorithm that is cache-oblivious and has low false sharing costs, which suggests that it belongs to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The algorithm is also designed for parallel execution on multicore computing environments, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper mentions the critical path length of the algorithm, which suggests that it could belong to the Performance (cs.PF) sub-category. The algorithm is also designed to be scheduled by a work-stealing scheduler, which suggests that it could belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions that the algorithm is resource oblivious, which suggests that it could belong to the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category.
